His assistant and anasthesiolgist were WONDERFUL and helped reassure me and calm me down. Following my procedure I called Imperial  Dental for a follow up to have my teeth looked at (I‚Äôm a very paranoid individual when it comes to my teeth) and they worked me in with Dr. Chung. Sometimes at the dentist you feel rushed, like you are just one more patient, however Dr. Chung really eased my worries and was very kind. Thank you Imperial Dental. <Text>:
In 2016 I took my daughter to this dental office they told me she needed 5 root canals and that it needed to be done asap. I didn't think my 10 year old needed that much work done on her mouth and I took her for a second opinion. She got an award at her new dentist for having no cavities! This made me wonder, has this happened before? I had 7 teeth pulled years ago at this dentist and I wonder if that was necessary? So I went and made an appointment and sure enough they wanted tok pull 2 more of my teeth after doing a root canal. I went to have a second opinion the next day and I only needed a fill and a cap. The porcelain tooth that Imperial Dental had put on years before was not put on correctly. I had the new dentist call for my daughter's records and they were told the records were lost, I called and was told the same. I brought this up with imperial and they told me different dentists diagnose differently. Well 5 root canals on a 10 year old with no cavities seems very different to me! I started to ask around and my mother had had a similar experience and now has a new dentist. I posted on FB and one story after another about insurance fraud and false diagnoses poured in. I don't know if what they are doing is illegal or just morally wrong but it needs to stop! Putting a child through that much pain and suffering for no reason?! Who would do that!? I am creating this group because I can't find another way of getting the information out there. Have you had a similar experience? Do you want to stop them from doing this to anyone else? Please join me, I need all of the help I can get!
Please check out my newly created group "Spreading the word about Imperial Dental yucaipa" I need your stories and your help. I've tried making posts on the Front Porch but was blocked. Please read my story and spread the word. They will have to stop if we make enough noise.</Text>< Pics>

< Review>
Amazing. I enjoy the shrimp coconut rolls, the pork rolls (don't know the actual name), and my go to is the red curry with chicken and extra veggies. My kids enjoy the fried rice and the prawn noodles. Don't forget to order dessert because it's soooo good!   The coconut jelly dessert (don't know the actual name) was great! Pricing is reasonable for a family and the quality of food is great!!<//Review>

<name>kris kelly</name><Gmap_id>0x80dce0f4bc7b1e1d:0xf628b21f583cec7f<//Gmap_id><time>1599961669116<//time></record></dataset><record>
<Rating>5</Rating>< text>
Moderately priced but hey Corona Del Mar leases I'm sure. Still prices were very reasonable. Had a friend that did deliveries locally and she noticed this location was popular. We went to have a slightly later lunch there for fun. Wow! Were we pleasantly surprised. This is Viet Cafe/Grill style, not a Pho house. Although they have some Pho style soup selections. For a later lunch around 2pm they had 80/90% covers filled so busy place for sit down service. Still the turn over for wait was very short. My friend had a lovely Thai Iced Tea, I had a house lager beer. We started with a simple beef satay. Nice marinade and the peanut sauce was delightful. Was pleased it wasn't chewy or over cooked. They had shrimp spring roll variety and crab (?) egg roll (?) also. The specials looked very tasty too, I recommend checking them. For entre, she had chicken/shrimp pad thai, they let her combo the proteins. Flavors were spot on for the Pad Thai. I had their specialty Shaken Beef. I've had it once before in Garden Grove. Basically trimmed fillet mignon, done with garlic, mushrooms and bell peppers. Similar to a Chinese pepper beef Szechuan style. However, the meat is cubed and better quality for Shaken Beef. I'd say the sauce is more rich too, very beefy and tangy dark sauce. Portions were spot on. For service they were busy but helpful. No reservation, walk-in. I liked the darker ambiance inside (posted pics). The macaroons and champagne in the front case looked like a tasty desert for a fancy occasion. Interesting the his/hers restroom is outside and common to the business center. Just ask for the key at the front central desk. To find I suggest be northbound on PCH, hard right turn just before the Chevron and before Mac Arthur. Restaurant is ahead on the corner on the right. Some street parking or more parking after a right turn in the neighborhood. Typical parking for the area is a bit tight, plan for a possible short walk. Don't park at Chevron, possible tow. Done with Thai food? Now go south on PCH, right at Goldenrod and follow to the beach for a pleasing sunset at the lookout. Ah, the charm of the crown of the sea. Good appetite fellow foodies :D< /text>

< Rating>

< text>
The Phuket noodle soup is the most mouth watering and flavorful seafood dish I have ever tried in my life.  Every time I come here, that is what I get.  There is no seafood soup as tantalizing as this.  The positives are that there is extensive parking in the street and around the restaurant, and this serves an amazing pan-Asian food.

The other negative is that the restroom is outside of the restaurant.  You actually have to walk around to get to it on the outside.  Also, unless you get reservations at night, you have to wait.  All in all, this is a fabulous gem of a place to dine out.  The prices may be a little higher than usual for Asian cuisines, but we are talking about Corona Del Mar in the nicest part of Newport Beach.< /text>

< review>
Excellent Thai/Vietnamese cuisine! Fried rices are outstanding, noodle dishes as well. Their crispy spring rolls that you wrap in a lettuce leaf are amazing. The Tom Kha (coconut) soup is very good. This is the first thing I have at Thai places, it usually gives a good idea of the quality. My recent favourite that I go back for every week is on the special of the month menu (3 months in a row luckily!), shrimp, crab and asparagus stir fried with egg. I am addicted to it! The place is small, I'm surprised they haven't tried moving into a bigger space, they are always full and very popular for take out.<//review>

Best Thai place in Newport Beach. The restaurant can probably seat around 50 but it does get quite crowded. The food is very good and service is prompt after you get seated. <UserId.>113994550675585396020< /UserId.><Name>Dillon Mendoza</Name><date>1482605214533<//date>< rate>

<Text>I won't lie to you guys. We went on a miniature adventure trying to locate this wonderful place. Can't decide if it's because we are special, or because this place is in such a tactical location that not even the hide and seek world champ of 2027 could find it. Anyways enough of that. Let's get down to business, to defeat the Huns. Woops. Those are lyrics to Mulan. Sorry.

Seriously though. This place is delicious and I would highly recommend it to any noodle loving food connoisseur. Upon arriving at this little eatery on the corner, directly across from a conveniently located gas station for all your late night needs, we were greeted by friendly staff eager to serve their customers. Not even thirty seconds had passed and we were already being asked where we would like to sit and being directed to a table. Before you could even get comfy in your chairs we were already being asked what we would like to drink, not that this is a bad thing because I'm a thirsty guy. But wait, there's more. "Would you like ice with your waters?"  You're damn right I'd love to put frozen water in my liquid water to make it a bit colder on an already cold and rainy night.

I had never been asked before if I would like ice in my water. Most restaurants assume it's something you want, but I was very pleased that they would even ask. Definitely brownie points. A little later into visit, after starting at their mouth watering menu for a solid twenty minutes me and my companion, who is very cute by the way, ordered the Chicken Pad Thai for herself and I ordered the Beef Pho Bowl, or Pho Bo for short. The wait wasn't too bad, about 10 minutes. Plus I'm a firm believer in hunger is the best seasoning. When the food came out and arrived at our table, I took one whiff of my dish and immediately went to a noodley heaven. I transcended through noodle space and time and found myself in a bathhouse. Except the water was not water. It was a rich and tasty beef broth that was capable of bringing even the toughest man to his knees, and a tear to his eye. Not unlike cherry pie by Warrant.

I felt like I was in a 5 gum commercial. Every seasoning was so pronounced. I could literally taste each flavor dancing on my tongue. At one point there was the macareina, and halfway through the bowl they changed it up and we're doing the tango. All while this was going on, I was slowly being wrapped up in a noodle blanket covering me from head to toe. I could die a happy man. The warm noodles radiating heat throughout my body. I could do the Polar Plunge naked up in Big Bear and not even flinch at the sheering icy winds or freezing water. Which I actually did earlier last week. My feet almost fell off it was so cold. But not today, because I was protected by a coat of hot noodles.

The Chicken Pad Thai was also very delicious. I had a couple of bites. Unfortunately not enough to transcend noodle space and time once more, but I would highly recommend the dish. Enough so that on a second visit it would be a strong contender for my next dish.

We also had the Singha beer which was surprisingly good. It was a lighter beer with a nice aftertaste. Complimented our dishes quite well. We originally wanted the Lucky Buddha, but unfortunately it was out. Guess I'm not getting lucky tonight :/

A brief description of the interior now. Picture this, you're on a train going through the desert. Nothing but sand for miles and miles in every direction as far as the eye can see, which largely depends on your sight. You may need contacts. Anyways that desert scene is exactly what this place isn't. This joint is very quaint and cozy, in the best way possible. If I had to guess you could have about 40 people eating here max. But it works perfectly. Bamboo accent all around the walls, nice wooded flooring and tables. Felt like home. If home was a delicious Vietnamese Fine Dining establishment. Anyways I would highly recommend this place. It would have got a 5/5 stars but the bathrooms are a mission to find.</Text>< pictures>

<text>Just over a week ago, my now husband and I hosted a wedding rehearsal and welcome dinner in Bamboo Bistro's private dining room upstairs from the main restaurant for about 50 guests. The owner Chau and her team worked so hard to make sure that all the guests were attended to and felt welcome, and ensured that there was WAY more food to go around. :) (my parents and relatives happily took what seemed like endless leftovers back to the hotel for the next day's breakfast and lunch). We're so grateful that we found this restaurant; everyone kept talking about how amazing the food, service, ambience and space was, and the quality of the wine. I can't even count how many people raved about the food and how fresh and tasty it was; we even had some people who had never tasted Vietnamese food come, but quickly became converts! We had many guests come from overseas, and now that they are back home, they still can't stop raving about the welcome dinner here!!

We knew we wanted something Vietnamese for our welcome dinner since there would be no Vietnamese food unfortunately at our wedding reception the day after, and we wanted it to be within 30 min. driving distance of San Clemente, where our wedding was. Westminster and Garden Grove, where most of the great Vietnamese restaurants are, would be way too far away, and we just happened to come across this place since it's a sister restaurant of Brodard Chateau.

The restaurant offers a number of multi-course banquet style menus, and all are incredible value for both the quantity and quality of the food. In fact, I think we chose the second cheapest option, but you'd never guess this based on the variety of dishes and proteins and how good the food was! The most popular dishes by far that were served were the seafood claypot, the shaking beef with garlic noodles, and the mango sticky rice. The tastes are authentic but with modern twists, which even pleased my Vietnamese mother, who is extremely skeptical of anything that is "modern" and not exactly like what she grew up eating in Vietnam. Setting up the private dinner arrangements and a few customizations was so smooth and seamless; Chau was quick to respond via email and incredibly apologetic (unnecessarily so) when she responded even just a day or two later).

The private dining room space is really beautiful - modern, but with lots of traditional Vietnamese touches and paintings/decorations. It felt so comfortable, cozy, and refined without trying too hard. It's like a bigger version of the main restaurant downstairs.

The service was super attentive and someone was always quick to come to my side whenever I needed even the slightest thing. I am really in love with Bamboo Bistro, the owner Chau, their menu and entire staff, and my husband and I are so grateful to have found them and had our welcome dinner there. When we are back in the area, we'd happily come back to eat here again and would recommend it without reservation for any meal or private dinner party.</text>< date>

<Name>kev pai<//Name><date>1614921786249</date>< rating>
4</rating>
<review>Monorom Cambodian Restaurant in Long Beach, California is a small intimate restaurant that's dishing out big flavor. They have an extensive menu that's bound to satisfy the taste buds of everyone in the family. The restaurant is located at the corner of Anaheim Street and Dawson Avenue at 2150 E Anaheim St, Long Beach, CA 90804. The shop is open 7 days a week from 9:00 am-8:30 pm. Indoor dining is still restricted but they do have outdoor dining in front of the restaurant. I visited the restaurant on two different occasions and tried two different dishes. It was delicious.

LEMONGRASS CHICKEN (BAI MONN CHA KROEUNG)¬† KROEUNG, a Cambodian distinctive and complex spice blend paste with a strong aroma of lemongrass. Stir-fried chicken with bell pepper, jalapeno, and onion.¬† $9.95 It was very flavorful and delicious.

PORRIDGE & BLOOD JELLY (BORBOR CHIEM JROUK)¬† Porridge is the quintessential Cambodian breakfast dish. Prepared with whole grain rice, pork belly, pork internals and pork blood jelly. Garnished with bean sprouts, fried garlic, cilantro and scallions. $9.95 This aromatic dish will warm you tummy and leave you satisfied all day long.< /review>< Pictures>

<UserId.>100628241609761386745</UserId.>< Name>
Jared Cohee</Name>
< Time>
1554088635549<//Time>
<rating>5<//rating>< Text>
CAMBODIA üá∞üá≠
Eat the World LA review:
One of the best reasons to fly to Long Beach rather than LAX, other than the ease of entry and exit unknown at the latter, is the chance to pop into one of the area restaurants. After dropping off my mother at the end of a recent visit, and an obligatory walk on the beach, we settled into a Saturday lunch before noon and found ourselves amongst a busy dining room dominated with a big group of eight.

Senmonorom is the capital of the eastern Mondulkiri Province, which borders Vietnam and is home to the indigenous Pnong people. Other than the name, this seems to be the only connection with this part of Cambodia as the menu sticks to a Khmer hit list which is very popular with the community here in Long Beach.

After having the life-changing plate of lot cha at Phnom Penh Noodle Shack, a few blocks north on Cherry Avenue, it is very difficult to resist a plate of it at any Cambodian restaurant. While the version here may not have the same effects, lot cha ($7.50) with chicken still was easily finished and enjoyed. By the time the food came it was noon and that of course was good enough reason to enjoy a cold Angkor Beer. You can find a lot of reasons to relax in Long Beach, but good Cambodian food and drink is at the top of any list.< /Text>

< Text>
Located at a busy intersection amidst the large Cambodian community in Southern California, this restaurant is very trendy, well decorated and provides authentic Khmer food. The soups with fish sauce and served on a hot plate is classy. This is one of the finest Cambodian restaurant in Southern California. During my third visit I ordered barbecue beef with rice, it was indeed fantastic. The plate was adorned with colourful vegetables and perfectly decorated.</Text>

<Review>The menu is quite varied, with vegetarian, seafood, beef, pork and chicken dishes of a wide variety. The lemongrass beef dish was richly flavored and spicy; the stir-fried watercress, with fish sauce and plenty of garlic, was particularly fine. The vegetarian egg roles were light and crisp, and the "student noodles" (similar to pad Thai but with a slightly different flavor) were a standout too. This is a superb restaurant, with sizable portions and absurdly low prices.< /Review>< Response>

<time>1551983471024< /time><Rating>4<//Rating>< Review>
The dishes were tasty, lots of flavor, herbs & spices, lots of garlic, even their dipping sauce came with a kick, and if this is not enough, try their hot pepper rack, yummy options for spicy lovers. The place is cozy, the wait staff is slow when there's are than 3 tables, but friendly, as expected for an Asian establishment, then again they serve authentic dishes. We would come again when in the area. All these were yummy:  Beef Noodle Soup Kuyteav Sach Goh (Beef Noodle Soup), Kuyteav Kohr Goh (Beef Stew Noodle Soup),  Phnom Penh Noodle Soup Kuyteav Phnom Penh (Phnom Penh Noodle Soup),  Thai Boat Kuyteav Thouk (Boat Noodle Soup), Pohr Vien M‚Äôpoang (Crispy Chitterlings) ‚Äì a La Carte, Sach Goh Lok Lak (Beef Lok Lak) ‚Äì a La Carte,  Dumplings. Size regular is sufficient to fill you up.<//Review>

Chhan Hak</name>
< Date>
1514981298182< /Date>
<rating>4< /rating><Text>Great local restaurant for authentic Cambodian food. The portions aren't as large as to other Cambodian restaurants in the area, a tad more expensive, as well. For the bang for your buck eater, a negative. As for me, I don't mind.

I've only tried their rice dishes and soup noddles. Fried Rice with Seasoned Beef(Lok-Lac); Beef and Seafood fried rice, which are all delicious. As for noddles, I've had the Phnom Penh Noddles (beef, shrimp, grounded pork and fish meatballs with rice noodles). Very delicious, as it doesn't steer away from the traditional ingredients/style. Surprisingly, the Thai Boat Noddles is great as well. One of the best I've tasted in Long Beach.

Tip: When ordering any rice dish, ask the server for a bowl of soup on the side. It'll enhance the dish and make it more enjoyable!< /Text><Pictures>None</Pictures><resp>None<//resp>< gmap_id>

<review>Updated Review:

This pandemic is hard on everyone. I know I need to grant others grace when needed. Lord knows there are many times where I need it and appreciate it when given to me.

Dr. Mee called me today to address the issues I was concerned about during my last visit. He was really kind and apologetic. It shows that he really cares about his patient‚Äôs experience. I know other business owners who attack people who negatively review their business. This was not the case. He ensured that the reuse of a cavi wipe is not the common practice and that it was addressed. Also, it‚Äôs been noted that I have a sensitivity to the epinephrine that‚Äôs in the lidocaine. I actually downplayed the reaction because I was trying not to full on panic while in the dental chair, so there was no way for Dr. Mee to know the severity of my reaction.

All in all, my last visit may have been an isolated incident, and it‚Äôs worth a third visit. I have kept my April visit and I have faith that it‚Äôll live up to the standards that have given this dental office their good reviews.

As with all reviews, each experience is different and the only real way to know, is to check it out for yourself.

Previous Review:
This was my second visit here. The first issue is that the girl at the front taking temperatures was reusing the same Cavi wipe to clean the thermometer between each use. First of all, that is never ok. Cross-contamination is always a concern. But especially now, in this pandemic that has taken so many lives, we all should be more vigilant to not cross-contaminate.

Secondly, I don‚Äôt know if Dr. Mee was really busy or maybe just not having a good day, but he just didn‚Äôt seem personable during this visit. Also, it‚Äôs the first time I‚Äôve ever had a reaction to the lidocaine in all the years that I‚Äôve been going to the dentist. To me, it was a really bad reaction: my heart was pounding, I was hot, and I felt like I was going to pass out. I was told it would pass in 5-10 minutes. It was very traumatizing.

Really not a good second visit. I have a cleaning scheduled in April, but I‚Äôm going to cancel. It‚Äôs great that many have had good experiences here, but I will be moving on.</review>< Pics>

< Review>
Dr. Mee is by far the best dentist I have ever visited.  I have had bad teeth ever since I was young.  I have memories of crying in the dentist's chair at 6 years old ( and a few times as an adult!).  I have never liked the dentist and would put off visits until I was in pain.  That has resulted in a lot of dental work over the years.  I was hesitant to see Dr. Mee, because of the amount of work that needed to be done, and just what bad shape my teeth were in.  But after some encouragement from family and assurance from him and staff that they were sure they had seen worse, I made my first visit.  I am so glad I did.  I have had 3 more visits since then and have been so happy with Dr. Mee, the pleasant atmosphere in his office, and his friendly and efficient staff.  I have never had to wait long in the outer office, I have had no pain during the procedures and no discomfort after the numbness wore off.  I was so surprised the first time I was injected.  Dr. Mee said "your will feel a pinch" and I felt no pinch, just some warming.  I worried about the long drive home after he finished a lot of major work.  The 6 hours back to Utah were no problem at all.  No pain.  Such a difference from the usual torn up gums and achy teeth I had come to expect after a long dentist's visit.  Dr. Mee's education and gentle techniques shine through.  His friendly, upbeat "chairside" manner put you at ease and make you feel unjudged.  My teeth look and feel so much better.  I will no longer put off regular cleanings and exams.  Dr. Mee and his staff have made such a difference in my oral health and the quality of my life.  Visit him.  You will immediately see the difference a GREAT dentist can make!  Thanks Dr. Eric Mee and staff!</Review>

<Name>Ken Nguyen<//Name><Date>1516390798263<//Date>< rate>
2</rate>
< text>
Came here for the first time to try some pupusas and soup. I ordered chicken soup and what I got was a plate of grilled chicken with rice/vegs with a side of soup(which was more expensive). When confronting the waitress about the wrong order, she said that if I wanted chicken soup with the chicken in the soup, you must clarify it. Apparently, simply saying chicken soup means you want a plate of grilled chicken and rice with a side soup instead of actually a bowl of soup with chicken. Anyways, the grilled chicken was good, but the soup itself was extremely salty. After a few spoonful, my tongue started to have that "burning" sensation you get from too much salt and this coming from someone that enjoys salty food. The pupusas I ordered were surprisingly good, however, I won't be back due to blatant upselling.<//text>

1< /rate>
< review>
Lowes has a 90-day refund policy for most of what they sell. We purchased custom window blinds through them. Lowes doesn't make custom blinds themselves, they job it out to 1 of 3 outside vendors, in our case, Bali. The Bali blinds are very poorly constructed and started to fall apart within 1 week of use. Unfortunately, this happened more than 90 days after we purchased them, because the room was being remodeled, and the blinds sat unwrapped in their boxes while the remodel was being finished. Lowes acknowledged the actual timing of use, and even acknowledged that the blinds were poorly constructed, but stuck to their policy anyway and offered not one penny of refund for a very expensive purchase that we're now stuck with. Much as I like Lowes for convenience & selection, I cannot shop there again or recommend them to anyone, especially not for anything custom-made from the flooring or wall covering depts.< /review>
